	<!-- <h2></h2> -->
			<div class="longform post_img fullwidth">
			<img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/baldwinscolor-copy.jpg" alt="" class="entry_post"/>
		</div>
				<h1>A Century of James Baldwin</h1>
		<h2>Celebrating 100 Years of a Great American Mind</h2>
    <div class="inner">
		<div class="post_header_wrapper">
    				</div>
				<div class="author_info" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
			<div class="author_name">By&nbsp;<a href="https://lithub.com/author/literary-hub/" itemprop="url"><span itemprop="name">Literary&nbsp;Hub</span></a></div>
			<div class="author_hr"><hr/></div>
			<div class="publish_date">August 2, 2024</div>
		</div>
		<div class="social_links">
						<a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=lithub&text=A+Century+of+James+Baldwin&url=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Fa-century-of-james-baldwin%2F"><span class="social_twitter"></span></a>
			<a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Fa-century-of-james-baldwin%2F&t=A+Century+of+James+Baldwin"><span class="social_facebook"></span></a>
					</div>
    <div class="inner">
    	<!-- Begin main content -->
    	<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
    			
										<!-- Begin each blog post -->
						<div class="post_wrapper" style="padding-top:0;">
							<div class="post_inner_wrapper">
						    	<div class="post_wrapper_inner">
										<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
								        
										<p>100 years ago, on August 2, 1924 James Baldwin, né James Arthur Jones, was born in New York City. Needless to say, he would grow to become one of America&#8217;s most important and beloved writers, thinkers, and social critics; his novels, essays, plays, poems, and criticism are essential reading for anyone who wants to understand this country—or the human condition.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><script id="9b7a21a47fb44523b011db6d4f4cad23">(new Image()).src = 'https://capi.connatix.com/tr/si?token=546998bb-b9c0-4480-8c91-3e307220efff&cid=86b7c382-5e20-4129-84db-dea768f4d688';  cnx.cmd.push(function() {    cnx({      playerId: "546998bb-b9c0-4480-8c91-3e307220efff"    }).render("9b7a21a47fb44523b011db6d4f4cad23");  });</script></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p>Though he died in 1987, Baldwin continues to have an outsize, but well deserved, influence on contemporary literature, activism, and criticism. We are grateful for his life and his work. Join Literary Hub in celebrating the centennial of Baldwin&#8217;s birth with a few of our favorite pieces on the writer from over the years.</p>
<h4><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="196405" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/how-did-james-baldwin-become-a-21st-century-influencer/james-baldwin-5/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin.jpeg" data-orig-size="800,401" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="James Baldwin" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-300x150.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin.jpeg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-196405" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin.jpeg" alt="James Baldwin" width="800" height="401" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin.jpeg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-300x150.jpeg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-768x385.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-60x30.jpeg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-50x25.jpeg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/10-reasons-to-love-james-baldwin-in-honor-of-his-100th-birthday/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>10 reasons to love James Baldwin, in honor of his 100th birthday.</strong></a><br />
By Brittany Allen</h4>
<p>James Baldwin would have turned a hundred years old today. There are far more than a hundred reasons to celebrate the man. A brilliant, complicated author and one of our most fearsome public intellectuals, he left cultural fingerprints everywhere. And not for nothing, his shadow seems to loom larger all the time.</p>
<p>It’s hard to know <a class="external" href="https://www.nypl.org/blog/2024/07/11/where-start-james-baldwin" target="_blank" rel="noopener">where to start</a> with a tribute, given the man’s output. So I may as well begin with abject praise. Here are ten reasons to keep celebrating a “<a class="external" href="https://www.macdowell.org/artists/james-baldwin?utm_source=newsletter&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=James%20Baldwin&amp;utm_campaign=2024jul_enews-1" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Black, poor, gay, and gifted…activist, humanist</a>.”</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/10-reasons-to-love-james-baldwin-in-honor-of-his-100th-birthday/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="93580" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/on-james-baldwins-radical-writing-for-playboy-magazine/james-baldwin-4/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/James-Baldwin.jpg" data-orig-size="800,420" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="James Baldwin" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/James-Baldwin-300x158.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/James-Baldwin.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-93580" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/James-Baldwin.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="420" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/James-Baldwin.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/James-Baldwin-300x158.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/James-Baldwin-768x403.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/towards-universality-on-reading-and-rereading-james-baldwins-sonnys-blues/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Towards Universality: On Reading—and Rereading—James Baldwin’s “Sonny’s Blues”</strong></a><br />
<em>Tom Jenks Considers the Eternal Power of a Masterpiece of American Short Fiction<br />
</em>By Tom Jenks</h4>
<p>I can’t recall with certainty when I first read James Baldwin’s “Sonny’s Blues,” but I had it well in mind in 1984 when Raymond Carver and I were selecting stories for our <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780440204237" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>American Short Story Masterpieces</em></a>. When Ray and I worked on our selections, we would meet in Manhattan, where I lived, or in Syracuse, New York, where he lived. Whichever of us had traveled brought a suitcase full of books, and the other contributed an accumulated stack. We’d trade books.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/towards-universality-on-reading-and-rereading-james-baldwins-sonnys-blues/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241016" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/colm-toibin-on-james-baldwins-enduring-international-influence/toibin-and-baldwin/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/toibin-and-baldwin.jpg" data-orig-size="1500,613" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="toibin and baldwin" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/toibin-and-baldwin-300x123.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/toibin-and-baldwin-1240x507.jpg" class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-241016" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/toibin-and-baldwin-1240x507.jpg" alt="" width="1240" height="507" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/toibin-and-baldwin-1240x507.jpg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/toibin-and-baldwin-300x123.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/toibin-and-baldwin-768x314.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/toibin-and-baldwin-60x25.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/toibin-and-baldwin-50x20.jpg 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/toibin-and-baldwin.jpg 1500w" sizes="(max-width: 1240px) 100vw, 1240px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/colm-toibin-on-james-baldwins-enduring-international-influence/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Colm Tóibín on James Baldwin’s Enduring, International Influence</strong></a><br />
<em>Caoilinn Hughes in Conversation with the Author of “On James Baldwin”</em><br />
By Caoilinn Hughes</h4>
<p><strong>Caoilinn Hughes</strong>: To begin at the beginning: there was the word. Both you and Baldwin temporarily heeded it and even preached it, or considered doing so. That early influence of the Church is there so clearly in Baldwin’s use of language, his incredible range and control of register, and it’s there in the temper of your prose, too. Is it fair to say you share that influence?</p>
<p><strong>Colm</strong> <strong>Tóibín: </strong>Enniscorthy, where I grew up, had a very close community and at the very center of it was the Catholic cathedral, and at the very center of that was the altar, at the very center of the altar were the priests, and then behind the priests, the altar boys, and I was an altar boy. So that whole idea of listening to language, as ritual… I was I suppose coming to consciousness really just as the Latin Mass changed to the English Mass, but I was there for the Latin Mass, and bits of the Latin Mass are still in my mind; <em>Sursum corda</em>, lift up your hearts.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p>And so it starts with being an altar boy for those Masses in Enniscorthy, the stained glass, the light, the Cathedral, the choir, the amazing choir singing Mozart… all of that mattered enormously, as did later at St. Peter’s, which was half a seminary and half a Diocesan school where a lot of the real influences on, certainly on me, were priests. And that came later with its ambiguities, but at the time it was very rich because the Diocesan priests were spending their summers in America because they were teacher-priests.</p>
<p>Therefore they were coming back in 1971 with all that stuff of the Civil Rights Movement and having debates about it. So that when I came to <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780375701870" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Go Tell It On a Mountain</em></a>, I was fascinated by the Civil Rights Movement.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/colm-toibin-on-james-baldwins-enduring-international-influence/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="241059" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/10-reasons-to-love-james-baldwin-in-honor-of-his-100th-birthday/jamesbaldwin-acydeonjamesbaldwin_srighteousstyle-gq020119-gyol-05-1/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/James20Baldwin-Acyde20on20James20Baldwin_s20Righteous20Style-GQ020119-GYOL-05-1.jpeg" data-orig-size="800,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="JamesBaldwin-AcydeonJamesBaldwin_sRighteousStyle-GQ020119-GYOL-05-1" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/James20Baldwin-Acyde20on20James20Baldwin_s20Righteous20Style-GQ020119-GYOL-05-1-300x169.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/James20Baldwin-Acyde20on20James20Baldwin_s20Righteous20Style-GQ020119-GYOL-05-1.jpeg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-241059" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/James20Baldwin-Acyde20on20James20Baldwin_s20Righteous20Style-GQ020119-GYOL-05-1.jpeg" alt="" width="800" height="450" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/James20Baldwin-Acyde20on20James20Baldwin_s20Righteous20Style-GQ020119-GYOL-05-1.jpeg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/James20Baldwin-Acyde20on20James20Baldwin_s20Righteous20Style-GQ020119-GYOL-05-1-300x169.jpeg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/James20Baldwin-Acyde20on20James20Baldwin_s20Righteous20Style-GQ020119-GYOL-05-1-768x432.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/James20Baldwin-Acyde20on20James20Baldwin_s20Righteous20Style-GQ020119-GYOL-05-1-60x34.jpeg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/James20Baldwin-Acyde20on20James20Baldwin_s20Righteous20Style-GQ020119-GYOL-05-1-50x28.jpeg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /><br />
<a href="https://lithub.com/the-many-lessons-from-james-baldwins-another-country/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Many Lessons from James Baldwin’s <em>Another Country</em></a></strong><br />
<em>Carole Burns Rediscovers a Masterclass in Craft</em><br />
By Carole Burns</h4>
<p>From the first page, I am immersed in the world of James Baldwin’s <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/40/9780679744719" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Another Country</em></a>.</p>
<p>It is Rufus’s world from the start. Rufus is a flawed character if there ever was one – and yet how deeply sympathetic I feel as he trudges the streets of New York City. Baldwin’s New York is always vivid and complicated and laden with a character’s history as well as its own. In the novel’s opening pages, Rufus revisits his past: The Avenue, the name Baldwin seems to use for every avenue in New York; the jazz bar where, only seven months earlier, Rufus was playing drums instead of looking in as a vagrant. He hopes and fears people inside will recognize him.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/the-many-lessons-from-james-baldwins-another-country/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="48190" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/james-baldwin-the-world-is-white-no-longer/andermatt-billionaire-resort/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/swiss-village.jpg" data-orig-size="1366,726" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;Via Bloomberg&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;The village of Andermatt, Switzerland, is seen in this undated handout photo, released to the media on Wednesday, Sept. 1, 2010. An Egyptian billionaire with a penchant for risk is transforming a sleepy Swiss village into a ritzy resort that may one day rival Verbier. Source: Andermatt Swiss Alps via Bloomberg EDITOR&#039;S NOTE: NO SALES. FOR EDITORIAL USE ONLY.&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;ANDERMATT BILLIONAIRE RESORT&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="ANDERMATT BILLIONAIRE RESORT" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/swiss-village-300x159.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/swiss-village-1240x659.jpg" class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-48190" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/swiss-village-1240x659.jpg" alt="" width="1240" height="659" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/swiss-village-1240x659.jpg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/swiss-village-300x159.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/swiss-village-768x408.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/swiss-village.jpg 1366w" sizes="(max-width: 1240px) 100vw, 1240px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://lithub.com/james-baldwin-the-world-is-white-no-longer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">James Baldwin: The World is White No Longer</a></strong><br />
<em>Read &#8220;Stranger in the Village&#8221; from Notes of a Native Son</em><br />
By James Baldwin</h4>
<p>From all available evidence no black man had ever set foot in this tiny Swiss village before I came. I was told before arriving that I would probably be a “sight” for the village; I took this to mean that people of my complexion were rarely seen in Switzerland, and also that city people are always something of a “sight” outside of the city. It did not occur to me—possibly because I am an American—that there could be people anywhere who had never seen a Negro.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><a href="https://lithub.com/james-baldwin-the-world-is-white-no-longer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">[Keep reading&#8230;]</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="60860" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/cornel-west-on-why-james-baldwin-matters-more-than-ever/screen-shot-2017-02-28-at-12-17-46-am/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Screen-Shot-2017-02-28-at-12.17.46-AM.png" data-orig-size="800,427" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Screen Shot 2017-02-28 at 12.17.46 AM" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Screen-Shot-2017-02-28-at-12.17.46-AM-300x160.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Screen-Shot-2017-02-28-at-12.17.46-AM.png" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-60860" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Screen-Shot-2017-02-28-at-12.17.46-AM.png" alt="" width="800" height="427" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Screen-Shot-2017-02-28-at-12.17.46-AM.png 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Screen-Shot-2017-02-28-at-12.17.46-AM-300x160.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Screen-Shot-2017-02-28-at-12.17.46-AM-768x410.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/cornel-west-on-why-james-baldwin-matters-more-than-ever/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Cornel West on Why James Baldwin Matters More Than Ever</strong></a><br />
<em>In Conversation with Christopher Lydon</em><br />
By Christopher Lydon</h4>
<p>James Baldwin was the prophetic voice of an era that isn’t over. Fifty years ago he was the intense man from Harlem who wrote, in essays and novels, his version of a civil-rights movement. Over the ruins of the 1960s, and specially the assassination of key leaders, black and white, James Baldwin spoke a sort of furious sad song for his country.</p>
<p>Activist-philosopher Cornel West writes and speaks in the James Baldwin tradition, in books like <em>Race Matters</em> and <em>Black Prophetic Fire</em>. You see him on television between Amy Goodman on Democracy Now and Sean Hannity on Fox, he’s back and forth as a teacher too, at Princeton and now at Harvard. In Andover Hall, the only gothic building on the Harvard campus, we sat down with West to learn about James Baldwin’s resonance today, in “as blues-like a moment as we can imagine.”</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/cornel-west-on-why-james-baldwin-matters-more-than-ever/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="231807" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/selfishly-curated-experiences-how-planning-trips-can-inform-novel-writing/istanbul-places-turkey-cityscape-sky-city-1617534-pxhere-com-1/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/istanbul-places-turkey-cityscape-sky-city-1617534-pxhere.com-1.jpg" data-orig-size="800,418" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="istanbul-places-turkey-cityscape-sky-city-1617534-pxhere.com (1)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/istanbul-places-turkey-cityscape-sky-city-1617534-pxhere.com-1-300x157.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/istanbul-places-turkey-cityscape-sky-city-1617534-pxhere.com-1.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-231807" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/istanbul-places-turkey-cityscape-sky-city-1617534-pxhere.com-1.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="418" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/istanbul-places-turkey-cityscape-sky-city-1617534-pxhere.com-1.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/istanbul-places-turkey-cityscape-sky-city-1617534-pxhere.com-1-300x157.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/istanbul-places-turkey-cityscape-sky-city-1617534-pxhere.com-1-768x401.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/istanbul-places-turkey-cityscape-sky-city-1617534-pxhere.com-1-60x31.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/istanbul-places-turkey-cityscape-sky-city-1617534-pxhere.com-1-50x26.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://lithub.com/james-baldwin-might-have-been-most-at-home-in-istanbul/">James Baldwin Might Have Been Most at Home in Istanbul</a><br />
</strong><em>Hilal Isler on Finding Home When You&#8217;re Not Looking for It</em><br />
By Hilal Isler</h4>
<p>When James Baldwin left home for Europe, he was broke. It was Armistice Day, 1948, when he sailed from New York to Paris, 40 bucks in his pocket. He would say he left not to go to France, but to get away from New York. He left because he had to.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/james-baldwin-might-have-been-most-at-home-in-istanbul/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="212552" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-to-read-before-and-after-seeing-james-baldwin-abroad/88ac0e76a03f575fc642e5a64c1cf214-4/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/88ac0e76a03f575fc642e5a64c1cf214.jpg" data-orig-size="1200,514" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="88ac0e76a03f575fc642e5a64c1cf214" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/88ac0e76a03f575fc642e5a64c1cf214-300x129.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/88ac0e76a03f575fc642e5a64c1cf214.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-212552" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/88ac0e76a03f575fc642e5a64c1cf214.jpg" alt="" width="1200" height="514" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/88ac0e76a03f575fc642e5a64c1cf214.jpg 1200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/88ac0e76a03f575fc642e5a64c1cf214-300x129.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/88ac0e76a03f575fc642e5a64c1cf214-768x329.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/88ac0e76a03f575fc642e5a64c1cf214-60x26.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/88ac0e76a03f575fc642e5a64c1cf214-50x21.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://lithub.com/james-baldwin-in-paris-on-the-virtuosic-shame-of-giovannis-room/">James Baldwin in Paris: On the Virtuosic Shame of <em>Giovanni’s Room</em></a></strong><br />
<em>&#8220;If France proffered him love, it also bathed him in a peculiar shade of loneliness.&#8221;</em><br />
By Gabrielle Bellot</h4>
<p class="p1"><span class="s1">Early in <i>Giovanni’s Room</i>, James Baldwin’s seminal novelistic exploration of queerness, the narrator, David, remembers the first time he held another man’s body close to his own. He has spent a day with his friend Joey in Brooklyn, astonished at “how good I felt . . . how fond of Joey.” Tired, they decide to spend the night in Joey’s apartment, but Joey finds himself too entranced by his friend’s form in the shadowy room to sleep. When he makes awkward conversation about still being up because a bedbug bit him, David and Joey move closer and closer together, until they are cuddling and kissing. The experience shocks David. “It was like holding in my hand some rare, exhausted, nearly doomed bird which I had miraculously happened to find,” he reflects. The comparison is remarkable; his moments of intimacy with Joey are at once new and old, new in that he is a virgin to this kind of experience, and old because he has been feeling a quiet thrumming of desire all day with Joey, even if he didn’t fully understand the words of that soft electric language inside him. It is a beautiful “miracle” of a moment. </span></p>
<p class="p1" style="text-align: center;"><span class="s1"><a href="https://lithub.com/james-baldwin-in-paris-on-the-virtuosic-shame-of-giovannis-room/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></span></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="212556" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-to-read-before-and-after-seeing-james-baldwin-abroad/ok-4-28-17-4/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Fig-2.29-768x574-1.jpg" data-orig-size="800,481" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;2.8&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;iPhone 4&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;OK - 4\/28\/17&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1403095010&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;3.85&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;125&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.058823529411765&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;OK - 4\/28\/17&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="OK &#8211; 4/28/17" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;OK &#8211; 4/28/17&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Fig-2.29-768x574-1-300x180.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Fig-2.29-768x574-1.jpg" class="size-full wp-image-212556 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Fig-2.29-768x574-1.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="481" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Fig-2.29-768x574-1.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Fig-2.29-768x574-1-300x180.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Fig-2.29-768x574-1-768x462.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Fig-2.29-768x574-1-60x36.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Fig-2.29-768x574-1-50x30.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://lithub.com/the-last-days-of-james-baldwins-house-in-the-south-of-france/">The Last Days of James Baldwin’s House in the South of France</a></strong><br />
<em>Where Miles Davis, Nina Simone, Stevie Wonder and More Once Met</em><br />
By Magdalena J. Zaborowska</h4>
<p>After my first sighting of Chez Baldwin in 2000, I traveled to other places important to the writer—from the streets of Harlem and Greenwich Village to Paris, to Istanbul, Ankara, and Bodrum—and met many people who knew him and shared living spaces with him, and who all confirmed his paradoxical need for a frantic nomadic lifestyle on the one hand, and, on the other, his fervent desire to establish a stable domestic routine in multiple locations. Intrigued by his late-life turn to domesticity as well as the increasing focus of his works on families, female characters, and black queer home life that are prominent in <em>Just above My Head</em> and <em>The Welcome Table</em>, I returned to Chez Baldwin in June 2014. By that time I had published a book on the writer’s Turkish decade and numerous articles about various aspects of his works.</p>
<p class="p1" style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/the-last-days-of-james-baldwins-house-in-the-south-of-france/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<h4><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="198343" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/on-domesticity-and-memory-in-james-baldwin-and-becky-suss/bs22-001-8-greenwood-place-1997-99/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/BS22.001-8-Greenwood-Place-1997-99.jpg" data-orig-size="1200,575" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;16&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;NIKON D850&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1644594780&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;35&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;200&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.005&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="BS22.001 8 Greenwood Place (1997-99)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/BS22.001-8-Greenwood-Place-1997-99-300x144.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/BS22.001-8-Greenwood-Place-1997-99.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-198343" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/BS22.001-8-Greenwood-Place-1997-99.jpg" alt="" width="1200" height="575" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/BS22.001-8-Greenwood-Place-1997-99.jpg 1200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/BS22.001-8-Greenwood-Place-1997-99-300x144.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/BS22.001-8-Greenwood-Place-1997-99-768x368.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/BS22.001-8-Greenwood-Place-1997-99-60x29.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/BS22.001-8-Greenwood-Place-1997-99-50x24.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/on-domesticity-and-memory-in-james-baldwin-and-becky-suss/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>On Domesticity and Memory in James Baldwin and Becky Suss</strong></a><br />
<em>Peter L’Official on Suss’s “Brand of Children’s Vision for Adults”</em><br />
By Peter L’Official</h4>
<p>In 1976, James Baldwin published his first and only children’s book, <em>Little Man, Little Man: A Story of Childhood</em>—a collaboration with French artist and illustrator Yoran Cazac. Described on its jacket cover as a “child’s story for adults,” the book drew on Baldwin’s own difficult experiences growing up as a Black boy in Harlem, though it was written partly at the request of another young, Black, New York City “little man.” Baldwin’s nephew, Tejan, would often ask his famous uncle when he would ever write a book about him, to which Baldwin responded in the form of the story’s four-year-old protagonist, TJ. The book, however, was not well-received upon publication.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/on-domesticity-and-memory-in-james-baldwin-and-becky-suss/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<h4><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="196405" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/how-did-james-baldwin-become-a-21st-century-influencer/james-baldwin-5/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin.jpeg" data-orig-size="800,401" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="James Baldwin" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-300x150.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin.jpeg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-196405" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin.jpeg" alt="James Baldwin" width="800" height="401" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin.jpeg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-300x150.jpeg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-768x385.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-60x30.jpeg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-50x25.jpeg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/how-did-james-baldwin-become-a-21st-century-influencer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>How Did James Baldwin Become a 21st-Century Influencer?</strong></a><br />
<em>Marc Lamont Hill and Todd Brewster on the Blessing and Curse of Shareability on Twitter</em><br />
By Marc Lamont Hill and Todd Brewster</h4>
<p>James Baldwin, who came of age as a cultural figure in the 1950s, is a 21st-century influencer.</p>
<p>Two quotes in particular—“Not everything that is faced can be changed; but nothing can be changed until it is faced” and “To be black and conscious in America is to be in a constant state of rage”—have been perhaps the most shared, but it will surprise no one who knows something about the man that scholars have uncovered James Baldwin quotes on Twitter representing multiple sides of the author’s personality. One researcher <a class="external" href="http://tweetsofanativeson.com/Publications/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">used reverse engineering</a> to delineate “six subtly different Baldwins” crafted from quotations that have “excised, revised, botched, remediated, and wielded Baldwin’s words anew.”</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/how-did-james-baldwin-become-a-21st-century-influencer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<h4><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="98252" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/write-a-sentence-as-clean-as-a-bone-and-other-advice-from-james-baldwin/baldwin-3/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/baldwin.jpg" data-orig-size="1200,500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="baldwin" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/baldwin-300x125.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/baldwin.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-98252" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/baldwin.jpg" alt="" width="1200" height="500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/baldwin.jpg 1200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/baldwin-300x125.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/baldwin-768x320.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/write-a-sentence-as-clean-as-a-bone-and-other-advice-from-james-baldwin/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>“Write a Sentence as Clean as a Bone” And Other Advice from James Baldwin</strong></a><br />
<em>You Can Never Go Wrong Listening to This Guy</em><br />
By Emily Temple</h4>
<p>Ninety-four years after his birth (and more than thirty since his death) James Baldwin remains an intellectual, moral, and creative touchstone for many Americans—whether writers, critics, or simply people trying to live well in the world. Baldwin was an accomplished novelist, a legendary essayist, and an important civil rights activist—and most importantly for our purposes here, the man knew how to write a great sentence. His birthday is as good an excuse as any to revisit some of his teachings about the craft, and to that end, I’ve collected some of his best literary <em>bon mots </em>from essays and interviews below.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><a href="https://lithub.com/write-a-sentence-as-clean-as-a-bone-and-other-advice-from-james-baldwin/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">[Keep reading&#8230;]</a></em></p>
<h4><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="68665" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-look-inside-james-baldwins-1884-page-fbi-file/james-baldwin-3/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/James-Baldwin.jpg" data-orig-size="1200,500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="James Baldwin" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/James-Baldwin-300x125.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/James-Baldwin.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-68665" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/James-Baldwin.jpg" alt="" width="1200" height="500" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/James-Baldwin.jpg 1200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/James-Baldwin-300x125.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/James-Baldwin-768x320.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/a-look-inside-james-baldwins-1884-page-fbi-file/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>A Look Inside James Baldwin’s 1,884 Page FBI File</strong></a><br />
<em>Memos on &#8220;Aliases,&#8221; Sexuality, and The Blood Counters</em><br />
By William J. Maxwell</h4>
<p>Baldwin was “Jimmy” to most of his friends and to himself as well when he meditated on the various aspects of his personality. The numerous “strangers called Jimmy Baldwin,” he observed of his own diversity, included an “older brother with all the egotism and rigidity that implies,” a “self-serving little boy,” and “a man” and “a woman, too. There are lots of people there.” This secret FBI summary made the mistake of treating variations on Baldwin’s name and identity as a set of potentially criminal pseudonyms. For the Bureau, “James Baldwin,” “James Arthur Baldwin,” “Jim Baldwin,” and “Jimmy Baldwin” were “aliases” needing correlation and correction.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/a-look-inside-james-baldwins-1884-page-fbi-file/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="99175" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/james-baldwins-childrens-book-will-help-you-see-the-world-with-fresh-eyes/little-man-little-man/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Little-Man-Little-Man.jpg" data-orig-size="800,420" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Little Man Little Man" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Little-Man-Little-Man-300x158.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Little-Man-Little-Man.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-99175" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Little-Man-Little-Man.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="420" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Little-Man-Little-Man.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Little-Man-Little-Man-300x158.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Little-Man-Little-Man-768x403.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/james-baldwins-childrens-book-will-help-you-see-the-world-with-fresh-eyes/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>James Baldwin’s Children’s Book Will Help You See the World with Fresh Eyes</strong></a><br />
<em>On Reissuing the Quietly Radical Little Man, Little Man</em><br />
By Nicholas Boggs</h4>
<p>2017 was a watershed year for the legacy of James Baldwin. <em>I Am Not Your Negro</em>, directed by Raoul Peck, was nominated for an Oscar for Best Documentary. Barry Jenkins, director of the Oscar-winning feature, <em>Moonlight</em>, announced that his next film will be an adaptation of Baldwin’s 1973 novel, <em>If Beale Street Could Talk</em>. On the front page of the <em>New York</em> <em>Times </em>came the news that the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture acquired a massive archive of Baldwin’s papers, now available for public view. Baldwin’s prophetic words on race relations continue to be quoted and engaged in national and international conversations about race with renewed force and urgency in the era of Black Lives Matter.</p>
<p>It is against this backdrop that a forgotten Baldwin book, entitled <a class="external" href="https://www.dukeupress.edu/little-man-little-man" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><em>Little Man, Little Man: A Story of Childhood</em>,</a> is being republished by Duke University Press today after more than 40 years of obscurity. Originally published in 1976 by Dial Press in the United States and Michael Joseph in London, the book’s formal innovation and subject matter—the lives of black children in Harlem—didn’t resonate with readers at the time, and it went quickly out-of-print, despite the fact that it was profoundly important to Baldwin, who called it a “celebration of the self-esteem of black children.”</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/james-baldwins-childrens-book-will-help-you-see-the-world-with-fresh-eyes/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<h4><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="72271" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/baldwin-vs-buckley-a-debate-we-shouldnt-need-as-important-as-ever/baldwin-buckley/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Baldwin-Buckley.jpg" data-orig-size="800,417" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Baldwin Buckley" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Baldwin-Buckley-300x156.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Baldwin-Buckley.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-72271" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Baldwin-Buckley.jpg" alt="baldwin buckley" width="800" height="417" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Baldwin-Buckley.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Baldwin-Buckley-300x156.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Baldwin-Buckley-768x400.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></h4>
<h4 class="post_title" style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://lithub.com/baldwin-vs-buckley-a-debate-we-shouldnt-need-as-important-as-ever/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Baldwin vs. Buckley: A Debate We Shouldn’t Need, As Important As Ever</a></strong><br />
Gabrielle Bellot on America&#8217;s Foundational Divide<br />
By Gabrielle Bellot</h4>
<p>“It comes as a great shock,” James Baldwin said in his epochal debate against William F. Buckley at Cambridge in 1965, “around the age of five, or six, or seven, to discover that the flag to which you have pledged allegiance, along with everybody else, has not pledged allegiance to you.” It was early in the debate. The already-prominent African-American writer was speaking first; his opponent, then the editor of the <em>National Review</em> and soon to become lionized particularly in conservative circles as a father of the American right, stared at Baldwin with the lazy eyes and fingers on chin of a patrician boredom. Baldwin—visibly somewhat awkward at having to defend a proposition he thought obvious, that “the American Dream is at the expense of the American Negro,” which was the debate’s motion—had begun by making a simple, yet necessary point, one that rings as true today, if not truer, than it did in 1965: that the answer to this question ultimately came down to one’s “system of reality.” That a flag may look the same on the surface to you or me, yet where we store it away inside us—what it means to us—differs so drastically as to make two flags out of one. That all flags, in a sense, are perhaps two, or three.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/baldwin-vs-buckley-a-debate-we-shouldnt-need-as-important-as-ever/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="224608" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/read-the-first-reviews-of-every-james-baldwin-novel/james-baldwin_featured/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/James-Baldwin_featured.png" data-orig-size="800,420" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="James-Baldwin_featured" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/James-Baldwin_featured-300x158.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/James-Baldwin_featured.png" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-224608" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/James-Baldwin_featured.png" alt="James-Baldwin_featured" width="800" height="420" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/James-Baldwin_featured.png 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/James-Baldwin_featured-300x158.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/James-Baldwin_featured-768x403.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/James-Baldwin_featured-60x32.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/James-Baldwin_featured-50x26.png 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /><br />
<strong><a href="https://lithub.com/read-the-first-reviews-of-every-james-baldwin-novel/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Read the first reviews of every James Baldwin novel.</a></strong><br />
By Dan Sheehan</h4>
<p>James Baldwin is widely considered to be one of the finest writers and public intellectuals this country has ever produced. A brilliant novelist, essayist, and social critic, his explorations of homosexuality, racism, and class struggle in America have had a profound influence on the work of a generation of socially conscious authors, as well as countless readers and contemporary civil rights activists.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/read-the-first-reviews-of-every-james-baldwin-novel/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="59288" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/totally-radically-baldwin-raoul-peck-on-i-am-not-your-negro/iamnotyournegro_01/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/iamnotyournegro_01.jpg" data-orig-size="1200,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="iamnotyournegro_01" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/iamnotyournegro_01-300x113.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/iamnotyournegro_01.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-59288" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/iamnotyournegro_01.jpg" alt="" width="1200" height="450" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/iamnotyournegro_01.jpg 1200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/iamnotyournegro_01-300x113.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/iamnotyournegro_01-768x288.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/totally-radically-baldwin-raoul-peck-on-i-am-not-your-negro/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Totally, Radically Baldwin: Raoul Peck on I Am Not Your Negro</strong></a><br />
<em>Craig Hubert Interviews the Director about his Oscar-Nominated Documentary</em><br />
By Craig Hubert</h4>
<p>In 1979, the writer James Baldwin began working on a new project. “Remember This House” was originally conceived as a piece written for The New Yorker that would be a tour through Baldwin’s memory of the civil rights movement. The article never happened—parts of the original idea eventually migrated to Pat Hartley &amp; Dick Fontaine’s documentary I Heard it Through the Grapevine (1982)—but as the decade progressed, Baldwin kept returning to project, over and over again. It became the foundation of a book proposal that was never completed, now focused on the intersecting lives of civil rights leaders Medgar Evers, Malcolm X, and Martin Luther King, Jr., and a film project with the Maysles Brothers that was discussed before Baldwin’s death in 1987.</p>
<p>When the Haitian filmmaker Raoul Peck began developing a film about James Baldwin around 2006, with the assistance of the author’s estate, he saw the unfinished “Remember This House” as the crucial centerpiece that, because of its cumulative stature and open-endedness, allowed him to bring Baldwin into conversation with a present-day audience. As a teenager, Peck had been transformed by Baldwin’s words, partly because there was a direct connection between writer and reader that couldn’t be found anywhere else. It felt like Baldwin was speaking right to him, and the film needed that same immediacy and focus.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/totally-radically-baldwin-raoul-peck-on-i-am-not-your-negro/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<h4 data-report-url="/it-has-absolutely-nothing-going-for-it-except-satan-read-james-baldwin-on-the-exorcist/"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="203239" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/it-has-absolutely-nothing-going-for-it-except-satan-read-james-baldwin-on-the-exorcist/theexorcist2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/TheExorcist2.jpg" data-orig-size="800,471" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="TheExorcist2" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/TheExorcist2-300x177.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/TheExorcist2.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-203239" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/TheExorcist2.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="471" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/TheExorcist2.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/TheExorcist2-300x177.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/TheExorcist2-768x452.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/TheExorcist2-60x35.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/TheExorcist2-50x29.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></h4>
<h4 style="text-align: center;" data-report-url="/it-has-absolutely-nothing-going-for-it-except-satan-read-james-baldwin-on-the-exorcist/"><strong><a href="https://lithub.com/it-has-absolutely-nothing-going-for-it-except-satan-read-james-baldwin-on-the-exorcist/">“It has absolutely nothing going for it, except Satan.” Read James Baldwin on <em>The Exorcist</em>.</a></strong><br />
by Emily Temple</h4>
<p>Though James Baldwin is best known and loved for his novels, essays, and oratory, he is not frequently remembered as a great film critic—though, as Noah Berlatsky wrote in <a class="external" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2014/04/the-most-powerful-piece-of-film-criticism-ever-written/359996/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Atlantic</em></a>, he should be. In 1976, Baldwin published <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780307275950" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Devil Finds Work</em></a>, a book-length essay about his life watching movies, and about the politics of art in America, and nature of film itself.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/it-has-absolutely-nothing-going-for-it-except-satan-read-james-baldwin-on-the-exorcist/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="73896" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/naked-ladies-and-weird-invisible-men/vintage-playboy-covers/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/vintage-playboy-covers.jpg" data-orig-size="800,420" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="vintage playboy covers" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/vintage-playboy-covers-300x158.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/vintage-playboy-covers.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-73896" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/vintage-playboy-covers.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="420" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/vintage-playboy-covers.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/vintage-playboy-covers-300x158.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/vintage-playboy-covers-768x403.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/on-james-baldwins-radical-writing-for-playboy-magazine/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>On James Baldwin’s Radical Writing for Playboy Magazine</strong></a><br />
<em>Masculine Fantasy and the Subversive Possibilities of Androgyny</em><br />
By Joseph Vogel</h4>
<p>James Baldwin submitted an essay, “Freaks and the American Ideal of Manhood,” to Walter Lowe Jr., the first African American editor of <em>Playboy</em> magazine. Its radical thesis—that misguided notions of masculinity were at the root of America’s moral quandary—was new for Baldwin (at least in emphasis) and a direct challenge to the magazine’s primary demographic.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/on-james-baldwins-radical-writing-for-playboy-magazine/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="47139" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/i-squatted-james-baldwins-house-in-order-to-save-it/baldwins-house/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Baldwins-House.jpg" data-orig-size="1024,520" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Baldwin&#8217;s House" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Baldwins-House-300x152.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Baldwins-House.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-47139" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Baldwins-House.jpg" alt="" width="1024" height="520" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Baldwins-House.jpg 1024w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Baldwins-House-300x152.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Baldwins-House-768x390.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/i-squatted-james-baldwins-house-in-order-to-save-it/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>I Squatted James Baldwin’s House in Order to Save It</strong></a><br />
<em>Shannon Cain on Preserving a Literary Legend&#8217;s Last Address</em><br />
By Shannon Cain</h4>
<p>To clean the floor of James Baldwin’s guest room would take 32 disposable cleaning wipes. I figured this out on my hands and knees, estimating the square footage of the terra cotta tile surface. There were 40 wipes in the package. If I used one wipe per roughly two square feet, I’d have enough. I was camping here without running water or electricity, but damned if I was going to live inside a dusty mess.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/i-squatted-james-baldwins-house-in-order-to-save-it/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="59475" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/behind-the-dedications-james-baldwin/baldwin6/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Baldwin6.jpg" data-orig-size="800,351" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Baldwin6" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Baldwin6-300x132.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Baldwin6.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-59475" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Baldwin6.jpg" alt="james baldwin" width="800" height="351" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Baldwin6.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Baldwin6-300x132.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Baldwin6-768x337.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><strong><a href="https://lithub.com/behind-the-dedications-james-baldwin/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Behind the Dedications: James Baldwin</a></strong><br />
<em>The People in His Life and In His Books&#8230;</em><br />
By Arvind Dilawar</h4>
<p>James Baldwin was, undoubtedly, a compassionate man. A Pentecostal junior minister in his teen years, Baldwin eventually left the church, but the Christian ideal of brotherly love suffused his writing. It is, for example, what he turns to at the conclusion of his essay “Notes of a Native Son” to confront the ongoing violence and indignity of racism in the United States, writing: “Hatred, which could destroy so much, never failed to destroy the man who hated and this was an immutable law.”</p>
<p>Baldwin’s work is not only full of compassion for humanity at large, but love for the individuals in his life as well. His affection is found in the fictional portrayals of actual people in his short stories, plays and novels, such as the semi-autobiographical <em>Go Tell It on the Mountain</em>. It’s present in the references to his family members and friends in his essays and articles. It is perhaps most conspicuous in the dedications of his books—although these inscriptions, without context, elude appreciation.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/behind-the-dedications-james-baldwin/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
