<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/what-if-we-werent-afraid-to-tell-the-hard-truths-chris-chalk-on-playing-james-baldwin/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>“What If We Weren’t Afraid to Tell the Hard Truths?” Chris Chalk on Playing James Baldwin</strong></a><br />
<em>“Being Baldwin requires you to be free. It’s mandatory.”</em><br />
by Dan Sheehan</h4>
<p>Chris Chalk may not be a household name just yet, but he’s on the cusp.</p>
<p>The North Carolina native burst onto the American theater scene in 2010 when he starred opposite Denzel Washington and Viola Davis in the Tony Award-winning Broadway revival of August Wilson’s <em>Fences</em>. Since then, you may have seen his supporting turns in <em>12 Years a Slave</em>, <em>Detroit</em>, <em>Justified</em>, <em>Homeland</em>, <em>The Newsroom</em>, or <em>Gotham</em>. Most recently, Chalk played Paul Drake—a troubled beat cop turned private investigator in 1930s Los Angeles—opposite Matthew Rhys in HBO’s acclaimed reboot of <em>Perry Mason</em>.</p>
<p>In <em>Capote Vs. the Swans</em>, the second season of the Ryan Murphy’s venomous anthology series <em>Feud</em>, Chalk plays none other than James Baldwin, who, in 1975, pays a flying visit to his old friend Truman Capote (Tom Hollander) in the midst of the latter’s alcoholic exile from New York high society.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/what-if-we-werent-afraid-to-tell-the-hard-truths-chris-chalk-on-playing-james-baldwin/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="195992" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/james-baldwin-writes-down-to-nobody-read-langston-hughes-1958-review-of-notes-of-a-native-son/james-baldwin-langston-hughes/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-Langston-Hughes.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="James Baldwin Langston Hughes" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-Langston-Hughes-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-Langston-Hughes.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-195992" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-Langston-Hughes.jpg" alt="James Baldwin Langston Hughes" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-Langston-Hughes.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-Langston-Hughes-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-Langston-Hughes-768x384.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-Langston-Hughes-60x30.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/James-Baldwin-Langston-Hughes-50x25.jpg 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/james-baldwin-writes-down-to-nobody-read-langston-hughes-1958-review-of-notes-of-a-native-son/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>“James Baldwin writes down to nobody.” Read Langston Hughes’ 1958 Review of Notes of a Native Son</strong></a><br />
<em>“He is trying very hard to write up to himself.”</em></p>
<p>“I think that one definition of the great artist might be the creator who projects the biggest dream in terms of the least person. There is something in Cervantes or Shakespeare, Beethoven or Rembrandt or Louis Armstrong that millions can understand. The American native son who signs his name James Baldwin is quite a ways off from fitting such a definition of a great artist in writing, but he is not as far off as many another writer who deals in picture captions of journalese in the hope of capturing and retaining a wide public. James Baldwin writes down to nobody, and he is trying very hard to write up to himself. As an essayist he is thought-provoking, tantalizing, irritating, abusing and amusing. And he uses words as the sea uses waves, to flow and beat, advance and retreat, rise and take a bow in disappearing.&#8221;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/james-baldwin-writes-down-to-nobody-read-langston-hughes-1958-review-of-notes-of-a-native-son/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="59158" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/totally-radically-baldwin-raoul-peck-on-i-am-not-your-negro/james-baldwin-2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/James-Baldwin.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="James Baldwin" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/James-Baldwin-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/James-Baldwin.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-59158" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/James-Baldwin.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/James-Baldwin.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/James-Baldwin-300x150.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/James-Baldwin-768x384.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/blacks-and-jews-fifty-five-years-after-james-baldwins-negroes-are-anti-semitic-because-theyre-anti-white/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Blacks and Jews: Fifty-Five Years After James Baldwin’s “Negroes Are Anti-Semitic Because They’re Anti-White”</strong></a><br />
<em>Terrence L. Johnson and Jacques Berlinerblau Dissect a Classic American Polemic, Still Relevant Today</em><br />
By Jacques Berlinerblau and Terrence L. Johnson</h4>
<p>James Baldwin’s landmark essay <a class="external" href="https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/books/98/03/29/specials/baldwin-antisem.html?_r=2" target="_blank" rel="noopener">“Negroes Are Anti-Semitic Because They’re Anti-White”</a> is alternatively nuanced and strident, exacting and scattershot, hopeful and fatalistic. It’s fairly prophetic too. As we mark the 55th anniversary of its publication let us acknowledge that, in spite of all the outrage (and confusion) the piece created, it was prescient in many ways.</p>
<p>Way back in April of 1967 Baldwin surmised that by being <i>white</i>,Jewish-Americans—even the many Jewish-Americans committed to social justice—were ensnared within a brutal system of what we now call “racial capitalism.” The economic asymmetries that the system engendered would, in Baldwin’s augury, doom the civil rights coalition that these minority groups had heroically forged. Too, these structural inequalities would corrode any authentic empathy Jews and Blacks may have felt for one another.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/blacks-and-jews-fifty-five-years-after-james-baldwins-negroes-are-anti-semitic-because-theyre-anti-white/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="188363" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/charles-j-shields-on-the-profound-and-playful-friendship-between-lorraine-hansberry-and-james-baldwin/james-baldwin-lorraine-hansberry/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/James-Baldwin-Lorraine-Hansberry.png" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="James Baldwin Lorraine Hansberry" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/James-Baldwin-Lorraine-Hansberry-300x150.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/James-Baldwin-Lorraine-Hansberry.png" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-188363" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/James-Baldwin-Lorraine-Hansberry.png" alt="James Baldwin Lorraine Hansberry" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/James-Baldwin-Lorraine-Hansberry.png 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/James-Baldwin-Lorraine-Hansberry-300x150.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/James-Baldwin-Lorraine-Hansberry-768x384.png 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/James-Baldwin-Lorraine-Hansberry-60x30.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/James-Baldwin-Lorraine-Hansberry-50x25.png 50w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></p>
<h4 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/charles-j-shields-on-the-profound-and-playful-friendship-between-lorraine-hansberry-and-james-baldwin/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Charles J. Shields on the Profound and Playful Friendship Between Lorraine Hansberry and James Baldwin</strong></a><br />
<em>“Baldwin loved her caustic wit.”</em><br />
By Charles J. Shields</h4>
<p>During that year of intense writing and rewriting, Hansberry became friends with James Baldwin. They met in April, at a workshop reading at the Actors Studio of his novel <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780345806567" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Giovanni’s Room</em></a>, which he had adapted into a play. The work is about an interracial love affair. In America, Baldwin said, “the sexual question and the racial question have always been intertwined.” Lorraine went out of curiosity.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/charles-j-shields-on-the-profound-and-playful-friendship-between-lorraine-hansberry-and-james-baldwin/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>[Keep reading&#8230;]</em></a></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="159501" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/where-blues-for-mister-charlie-fits-into-james-baldwins-oeuvre/schrijver_james_baldwin_presenteert_nieuw_boek_op_persconferentie_in_americainho_bestanddeelnr_927-5825-1/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Schrijver_James_Baldwin_presenteert_nieuw_boek_op_persconferentie_in_Americainho_Bestanddeelnr_927-5825-1.jpg" data-orig-size="800,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Schrijver_James_Baldwin_presenteert_nieuw_boek_op_persconferentie_in_Americainho,_Bestanddeelnr_927-5825 (1)" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Schrijver_James_Baldwin_presenteert_nieuw_boek_op_persconferentie_in_Americainho_Bestanddeelnr_927-5825-1-300x150.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Schrijver_James_Baldwin_presenteert_nieuw_boek_op_persconferentie_in_Americainho_Bestanddeelnr_927-5825-1.jpg" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-159501" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Schrijver_James_Baldwin_presenteert_nieuw_boek_op_persconferentie_in_Americainho_Bestanddeelnr_927-5825-1.jpg" alt="" width="800" height="400" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Schrijver_James_Baldwin_presenteert_nieuw_boek_op_persconferentie_in_Americainho_Bestanddeelnr_927-5825-1.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/Schrijver_James_Baldwin_presenteert_nieuw_boek_op_persconferentie_in_Americainho_